**1. Purpose and Scope**

This document defines the node types, edge types, field schemas, and
canonical structure of the U.S. Law Knowledge Graph. It is the
authoritative source for graph contributors and pipeline engineers.

This is Document 1 of 4. The companion documents are:

> * Validation Spec --- all validation rules, error codes, and validator
> implementation guidance
>
> * Editorial Conventions --- label rules, description standards,
> disputed doctrine handling, contribution workflow
>
> * Serialization & Pipeline Spec --- JSON-LD format, Neo4j import,
> CourtListener integration

MVP scope is Constitutional Law. The schema is designed to extend to
federal statutory, regulatory, and state law in Phase 2.

**2. Design Principles**

**2.1 DAG, not tree**

The graph is a directed acyclic graph. Legal concepts appear in multiple
doctrinal contexts. Every node has exactly one primary parent for
navigation and may have secondary parents for cross-referencing.

**2.2 Separation of taxonomy and authority**

Taxonomy nodes represent legal concepts (Area, Doctrine, DoctrinalTest).
Authority nodes represent legal sources (Case, ConstitutionalProvision,
Statute, Regulation). A case is never a taxonomy node. A doctrine is
never an authority node.

**2.3 Temporal validity**

Every node and edge carries valid_from and valid_until. valid_until:
null means currently good law. Overruled cases and superseded doctrines
are never deleted --- they remain as historical record with valid_until
populated.

**2.4 Jurisdiction first**

Every node carries jurisdiction metadata. Circuit splits are modeled
through jurisdiction-scoped edge attributes, not duplicate nodes. See
Section 3.3.1 for the v0.4 court model.

**2.5 Machine-readable by default**

All IDs are stable lowercase_snake_case slugs. All dates are ISO 8601.
All enums are lowercase snake_case. The graph serializes as JSON-LD with
deterministic mapping to Neo4j via the provided import scripts.

**2.6 Doctrinal lineage is explicit**

The graph represents not just current law but how it got there ---
including intellectual lineage through non-majority opinions. The
intellectual_source[] field on DoctrinalTest and the
INTELLECTUALLY_PRECEDES edge type make this explicit.

**2.7 Canonical vs. derived fields (v0.4)**

  -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Value**                          **Meaning**        **Notes**
  ---------------------------------- ------------------ -------------------------------
  **Area.parent_id**                 Denormalized       CHILD_OF edge is canonical.
                                     convenience field  parent_id must match CHILD_OF
                                                        edge target.

  **DoctrinalTest.source_case_id**   Denormalized       ESTABLISHES edge is canonical.
                                     convenience field  source_case_id must match the
                                                        ESTABLISHES edge source.

  **Case.precedential_weight**       Derived summary    Derived from court_level +
                                     field              status. Validator warns if
                                                        inconsistent.
  -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Rule: when a field is denormalized, the edge is always canonical.

**2.8 Promotion rules (v0.4)**

A concept must be promoted from enum/attribute to first-class node when
it meets two or more of:

1. Recurs across multiple doctrinal areas
2. Has its own historical lineage
3. Is the logical target of multiple edges from different source nodes
4. Requires jurisdiction or time variation
5. Is queried independently by the research tool

**3. Node Types**

**3.1 Area**

Doctrinal areas of law forming the taxonomy spine.

Required fields: id, label, description, parent_id (null for root),
jurisdiction[], tier, status, valid_from, valid_until.

New in v0.5: jurisdiction[] and tier are now required.

tier values: 0 (root: constitutional_law), 1 (top-level:
individual_rights), 2 (doctrinal area: first_amendment, equal_protection),
3 (sub-area: commercial_speech, suspect_classification_doctrine).

**3.2 Doctrine**

Specific legal principles or frameworks within an Area.

Required fields: id, label, description, area_id, status, valid_from,
valid_until.

Optional fields: scrutiny_level, burden, elements[], notes,
pending_establishment[].

**3.2.1 pending_establishment[] --- transitional field**

When a Doctrine is modeled before the Case that established it is added
to the graph, use pending_establishment[] to record the anticipated
ESTABLISHES relationship. Format: [{ case_id, case_name, year, note }].

When the relevant slice is added: remove the pending_establishment entry
and add the ESTABLISHES edge. A stale entry (two slices added without
resolution) triggers W002.

**3.3 DoctrinalTest**

Formalized multi-prong tests. Subtype of Doctrine with structured prong
schema.

Required fields: id, label, description, area_id, source_case_id,
scrutiny_level, burden, test_form, prongs[], status, valid_from,
valid_until.

New in v0.5: source_case_id, scrutiny_level, burden, and test_form are
now required at the top-level DoctrinalTest node.

test_form values: conjunctive | disjunctive | balancing |
threshold_then_conjunctive.

scrutiny_level values: strict | intermediate | rational_basis |
heightened | per_se | balancing | none.

burden values: government | challenger | shared.

**3.3.1 Prong sub-schema**

Each prong: { number, label, description, burden_note, valid_from,
valid_until, contested (bool), contest_note }.

contested: true requires a non-empty contest_note.

**3.4 Case**

Judicial decisions. Authority nodes.

Required fields: id, short_name, full_name, citation, court_level,
court_name, binding_scope, decided_date, opinion_form,
procedural_disposition, holding, holding_type, majority_author,
per_curiam, vote, status, precedential_weight, valid_from, valid_until.

Optional fields: opinions[], notes, courtlistener_id, data_tier.

New in v0.5: courtlistener_id and data_tier formally recognized as
optional fields.

data_tier values: curated | auto_imported | inferred.

**3.4.1 opinions[] sub-schema**

Each opinion: { type, author, joined_by[], doctrinal_significance,
adopted_in[] }.

type values: dissent | concurrence | plurality | concurrence_in_judgment.

adopted_in[] records case IDs where this opinion's reasoning was later
adopted as majority law --- the source data for INTELLECTUALLY_PRECEDES
edges.

**3.4.2 per_curiam rule**

If per_curiam: true, majority_author must be null.
If per_curiam: false, majority_author should be set.
If opinion_form is per_curiam, per_curiam must be true.

**3.5 ConstitutionalProvision**

Articles, Sections, Clauses, and Amendments of the U.S. Constitution.

Required fields: id, label, text, provision_type, ratified_date, status.

New in v0.5 --- provision_type values: amendment | section | clause |
article.

Hierarchy: amendment-level nodes are top level. Section-level nodes
(e.g., amendment_14_section_1) are children of multi-section amendments.
Clause-level nodes (e.g., amendment_5_due_process,
amendment_5_self_incrimination) are children of sections or amendments.
Relationship between levels: INCORPORATES edge from child to parent.

Label convention: citation form only. Never use common name as label.
Examples: "U.S. Const. amend. V (Due Process Clause)", "U.S. Const.
amend. XIV, § 1". See Editorial Conventions, Section 1.1.

**3.6 Statute** [Phase 2 --- node type reserved]

**3.7 Regulation** [Phase 2 --- node type reserved]

**4. Edge Types**

**4.1 Edge type compatibility matrix**

  -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Edge Type**           **Source -> Target**                 **Required Attributes**
  ----------------------- ------------------------------------ ----------------------------
  CHILD_OF                Area -> Area                         --

  RELATED_TO              Area -> Area                         --

  INCORPORATES            ConstitutionalProvision ->           --
                          ConstitutionalProvision

  GROUNDED_IN             Area or Doctrine ->                  --
                          ConstitutionalProvision

  GOVERNED_BY             Area -> Doctrine or DoctrinalTest    condition (optional)

  ESTABLISHES             Case -> Doctrine or DoctrinalTest    --

  APPLIES                 Case -> Doctrine or DoctrinalTest    Not allowed when MODIFIES
                                                               exists for same source/target

  MODIFIES                Case -> Doctrine or DoctrinalTest    direction (required)

  OVERRULES               Case -> Case                         overrule_type (required)

  INTERPRETS              Case -> ConstitutionalProvision      --

  DISTINGUISHES           Case -> Case                         --

  CIRCUIT_SPLIT           Case -> Case                         Both must be circuit-level;
                                                               different courts

  INTELLECTUALLY_PRECEDES Case -> Case                         opinion_ref (required)

  PRECONDITION_TO         Doctrine -> Doctrine or             condition_note (required)
                          DoctrinalTest                        New in v0.5
  -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

**4.2 MODIFIES --- direction attribute**

  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Value**         **Meaning**                     **Example**
  ----------------- ------------------------------- -------------------------
  narrows           Tightens doctrine, reduces       44 Liquormart tightening
                    scope or government power        Central Hudson prongs 3-4

  expands           Broadens doctrine, extends       Shapiro extending travel
                    scope or government power        right to welfare residency

  clarifies         Resolves ambiguity without       Hess v. Indiana on
                    clearly narrowing or expanding   Brandenburg imminence

  complicates       Introduces new uncertainty,      Vieth v. Jubelirer on
                    leaves question open             Bandemer justiciability

  repudiates        Rejects key reasoning without    44 Liquormart rejecting
                    formally overruling              Posadas greater-includes-
                                                     lesser logic

  extends           Applies doctrine in new context  Claiborne Hardware
                    without changing prongs          extending Brandenburg to
                                                     civil liability
  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

**4.3 RELATED_TO --- editorial criteria**

All three conditions required:

> * Shared constitutional grounding (both areas GROUNDED_IN same provision,
> or one area's doctrine explicitly applied in other's cases)
>
> * Overlapping case law (at least one case in both lineages)
>
> * Complementary, not hierarchical (if one is a subset, use CHILD_OF)

**4.4 INTELLECTUALLY_PRECEDES --- opinion_ref attribute**

Required attribute opinion_ref: { case_id, opinion_type, author, note }.

opinion_type values: dissent | concurrence | plurality | majority.

New in v0.5: majority added. Use when a majority opinion in one case
directly originated reasoning a later case adopted or extended. Example:
Loving v. Virginia's recognition of marriage as a fundamental right
(majority) intellectually preceded Obergefell v. Hodges.

Canonical dissent example: Holmes's Abrams dissent (1919) → Brandenburg
majority (1969).

**4.5 GOVERNED_BY --- condition attribute**

Optional: { instrument_type (licensing_scheme | judicial_injunction |
administrative_order | statute | regulation), context, note }.

Use when an area is governed by different tests depending on the
government instrument. Example: prior_restraint governed by
prior_restraint_test for licensing schemes and by madsen_injunction_test
for content-neutral injunctions.

**4.6 OVERRULES --- overrule_type and cascade rule**

overrule_type values: explicit | implicit | effective | partial.

New in v0.5: partial added. Use when a case overrules another only in
a defined doctrinal context. When using partial, notes must specify the
scope. Example: Brown v. Board overruled Plessy in the field of public
education (partial).

Cascade rule: when OVERRULES edge added, validator surfaces W001 listing
all Doctrine and DoctrinalTest nodes ESTABLISHED by the overruled Case.
Contributor must confirm whether each also needs OVERRULES or survives.

**4.7 PRECONDITION_TO --- New in v0.5**

Models threshold doctrines: Doctrine A must be satisfied before Test B
applies.

Source: Doctrine node (the threshold gate).
Target: Doctrine or DoctrinalTest (what becomes applicable on satisfaction).

Required attribute condition_note: string describing what must be
satisfied and what outcome follows.

Use when: a doctrine functions as a threshold question that, if
satisfied, changes the applicable standard of review or legal test.

Canonical examples:

  discriminatory_intent_doctrine --[PRECONDITION_TO]--> strict_scrutiny_ep_test
  Condition: Proof of discriminatory purpose required before strict scrutiny
  applies to facially neutral laws. (Washington v. Davis, 1976)

  standing_doctrine --[PRECONDITION_TO]--> merits_review
  Condition: Article III standing must be established before court reaches
  constitutional merits.

**5. Temporal Model**

**5.1 Validity windows**

valid_from and valid_until on all nodes and edges. valid_until: null =
currently good law.

**5.2 Overruled cases**

When B overrules A: add OVERRULES edge B->A; set valid_until on A to
date of B; set status to overruled. Apply cascade rule. Do not delete A.

For partial overrulings: set overrule_type: partial; document scope in
notes; do not set valid_until on A unless wholly superseded.

**5.3 Historical edges**

Any edge with valid_until populated is a historical edge. Historical
GOVERNED_BY edges should have a corresponding OVERRULES or MODIFIES edge.

**5.4 Circuit splits**

CIRCUIT_SPLIT edge between conflicting Case nodes, jurisdiction-scoped.

**5.5 Mooted cases**

status: mooted, valid_until: mootness date, precedential_weight: none.

